{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"834"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/834"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.04,0.21,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41964"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/834"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26953"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"547"},{"type":"tags","id":"2092"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44927"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41964"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old woman presents with a three month history of a painless lesion on the lateral aspect of the tongue as shown in the photograph (Image). She initially thought it would go away by itself so did not visit the doctor but it has persisted. She has no significant past medical history and takes no regular medications. The patient has a 40 pack-year smoking history and frequently drinks a bottle of wine over 2-3 days. She is happily married to her husband of 30 years and denies any other sexual partners.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous cell carcinoma","Syphilitic ulceration","Leukoplakia","Traumatic ulceration","HIV-associated ulceration"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first and most important differential to think about in any non-healing mouth ulcer is oral \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (SCC) and all non-healing lesions must be biopsied to exclude cancer. The patient has risk factors for oral SCC including her smoking history and increased alcohol intake. The lesion is not consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eleukoplakia\u003C/strong\u003E which usually appear as thickened white patches in the mouth and can result from recurrent trauma or be a precancerous lesion. It is unlikely to be \u003Cstrong\u003Etraumatic ulceration\u003C/strong\u003E as that usually heals within 3 months. She is at very low risk of developing \u003Cstrong\u003Esyphilis\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003EHIV\u003C/strong\u003E with only having one heterosexual partner in the past 30 years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Smoking and alcohol are important risk factors for oropharyngeal cancers."],"references":["Wong T, Yap T, Wiesenfeld D. Common benign and malignant oral mucosal disease. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020 Sep;49(9):568."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26953"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18426"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18426"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"